  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is considered a criminal offense in most jurisdictions worldwide. It is typically addressed under criminal legislation and financial crime statutes. In many countries, money laundering is a serious criminal offense that involves:\n\n1. Concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n2. Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n3. Making funds from criminal activities appear legitimate\n\nSpecific legal frameworks and penalties vary by country, but money laundering is generally prosecuted as a criminal act with potential consequences including:\n\n- Criminal charges\n- Significant fines\n- Imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n- International legal cooperation for prosecution\n\nMost developed countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations to prevent and prosecute such activities.",
